Introduction

Link to dataset via nflverse GitHub repository: https://github.com/nflverse/nflverse-data/releases/download/player_stats/player_stats_season_2024.rds

Dataset consists of 1370 observations of 52 variables. Each observation is one NFL player. The 52 variables consist of: - nominal variables such as the NFL player’s name, a unique ID, the team who rostered the player, the position they played at on that team, and a URL to a headshot of the player - numeric variables such as the amount of games the player appeared, positional statistics like passing attempts, passing completions, passing/rushing/receiving yards, and passing/rushing/receiving touchdowns - the discrete variables standard and point per reception (PPR) fantasy points - continuous variables like positional EPAs, PACR, Dakota, and other composite data

Motivations for choosing this dataset are a complete picture of the 2024 season with which I could analyze to give further insight into my personal hobby of fantasy football.

Filtering, mutation, and selection of fantasy football related statistics

The following code block filters for NFL positions which comprise a fantasy football team, mutates per game statistics and net statistics to clarify point calculations, and deselects variables which do not contribute to point calculations.

nfl_stats <- nfl_stats %>%
  filter(position_group %in% c("QB", "RB", "WR", "TE"),
         season_type == "REG") %>%
  mutate(passing_yards_per_game = passing_yards / games,
         passing_tds_per_game = passing_tds / games,
         net_rushing_yards = rushing_yards - sack_yards,
         fumbles_lost = sack_fumbles_lost + rushing_fumbles_lost + receiving_fumbles_lost,
         converted_passing_air_yards = passing_yards - passing_yards_after_catch,
         rushing_yards_per_game = rushing_yards / games,
         rushing_tds_per_game = rushing_tds / games,
         receiving_yards_per_game = receiving_yards / games,
         receiving_tds_per_game = receiving_tds / games,
         receiving_air_yards_per_game = receiving_air_yards / games,
         fantasy_points_per_game = fantasy_points_ppr / games,
         targets_per_game = targets / games) %>%
  select(-season, -player_name, -season_type, -player_id, -player_display_name, -position, -headshot_url, -recent_team, -completions, -attempts, -sack_fumbles, -passing_first_downs, -passing_2pt_conversions, -carries, -rushing_fumbles, -rushing_first_downs, -rushing_2pt_conversions, -receiving_fumbles, -receiving_first_downs, -receiving_2pt_conversions, -special_teams_tds, -fantasy_points, -passing_epa, -rushing_epa, -receiving_epa, -dakota)

To filter out players who did not play regularly and might skew the data with outliers, I mutated a variable for the mean games played by a NFL player in the 2024 season and filtered for those who played at least the floor of the mean games played.

mean_games <- mean(nfl_stats$games)
nfl_stats <- nfl_stats %>%
  mutate(reg_player = if_else(games >= floor(mean_games), TRUE, FALSE)) %>%
  filter(reg_player == TRUE) %>%
  select(-games, -reg_player)

In order to tailor the datset to only fantasy rosterable players, I used the standard roster construction, 1 QB, 2 RB, 2 WR, 1 TE, to find the top fantasy players for each NFL team.

nfl_stats <- nfl_stats %>%
  group_by(position_group) %>%
  mutate(rank_fppg = rank(-fantasy_points_per_game)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(fantasy_rosterable =  case_when(
    position_group == "QB" & rank_fppg <= 32 ~ TRUE,
    position_group == "RB" & rank_fppg <= 64 ~ TRUE,
    position_group == "WR" & rank_fppg <= 64 ~ TRUE,
    position_group == "TE" & rank_fppg <= 32 ~ TRUE,
    TRUE ~ FALSE
  )) %>%
  filter(fantasy_rosterable == TRUE) %>%
  select(-rank_fppg, -fantasy_points_ppr, -fantasy_rosterable)

The goal of this project was to provide insights into optimal fantasy roster construction. Exploratory analysis began by creating a boxplot of fantasy positions and their fantasy points per game (FPPG).

Boxplot analyzing positional value

I then summarized the data to help identify positional value:

position_variability <- nfl_stats %>%
  group_by(position_group) %>%
  summarise(
    Q1 = quantile(fantasy_points_per_game, 0.25),
    Q3 = quantile(fantasy_points_per_game, 0.75),
    IQR = Q3 - Q1,
    mean = mean(fantasy_points_per_game)
  )

The next step would be to insure that FPPG was normally distributed across positional groups, if a histogram of each position showed this to be true, then FPPG should be the focus of my report.

Creating a dataset which focuses on QB observations and relevant variables

qb_stats <- nfl_stats %>%
  filter(position_group == "QB") %>%
  select(-position_group, -receptions, -targets, -receiving_yards, -receiving_tds, -receiving_fumbles_lost, -receiving_air_yards, -receiving_yards_after_catch, -racr, -target_share, -air_yards_share, -wopr, -receiving_yards_per_game, -receiving_tds_per_game, -receiving_air_yards_per_game, -targets_per_game)

To identify which variables had the highest correlation with fantasy points, I used a correlation matrix across all variables.

correlation_matrix <- qb_stats %>%

Interpretations

According to the correlation matrix, the variables most closely associated with what makes a good fantasy QB are passing touchdowns and passing yards. This is not surprising, as that is the primary role of a quarterback.

I instead chose to look for a variable which might not be apparent to most fans and found rushing yards to provide a high correlation as well.

model <- lm(fantasy_points_per_game ~ rushing_yards, data = qb_stats)

Interpretations

  • The intercept represents the mean number of points per game a QB will account for without a single rushing yard – 13.4 points.
  • The slope of the line is 0.01, which is exactly how many points a rushing yard is worth, so no surprises there.
  • A t-value represents the strength of the effect of rushing yards on fantasy points per game, meaning it is over 4 times the randomness in the data.
  • The p-value is very low, which tells us the relationship between rushing yards and points per game.
  • An adjusted R-squared of .36 represents rushing yardage accounts for over 1/3 of the variability in points per game

Mutating the dual-threat quarterback binary variable

Our null hypothesis will be that there is no difference between QBs who rush the ball well and those who do not. To perform a welch two sample t-test, I mutated a binary variable which represents rushing quarterbacks.

The mutated the binary variable dual-threat, based upon whether a QB accumulated one standard deviation above the mean rushing yards for a QB.

mean_qb_rush <- mean(qb_stats$rushing_yards)
sd_qb_rush <- sd(qb_stats$rushing_yards)
rushing_qb_threshold <- mean_qb_rush + sd_qb_rush
qb_stats <- qb_stats %>%
  mutate(dual_threat = if_else(rushing_yards >= floor(rushing_qb_threshold), TRUE, FALSE))

Dual-threat QB boxplot

dual_threat_boxplot <- ggplot(qb_stats, aes(dual_threat, fantasy_points_per_game)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(color = dual_threat)) +
  labs(
    title = "Dual-Threat QB's vs Pocket Passers",
    x = "Dual-Threat",
    y = "Fantasy Points Per Game"
  )
print(dual_threat_boxplot)

Interpretations

The boxplot reinforces the separation between dual-threat quarterbacks and pocket passers when accounting for fantasy points per game.

Welch two sample t-test

t_test_result <- t.test(fantasy_points_per_game ~ dual_threat, data = qb_stats)

t_test_result
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  fantasy_points_per_game by dual_threat
## t = -4.3837, df = 5.6584, p-value = 0.00534
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group FALSE and group TRUE is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -9.826974 -2.719828
## sample estimates:
## mean in group FALSE  mean in group TRUE 
##             15.3288             21.6022

Interpretations

A low p-value tells us this is statistically significant, and with a difference in means of greater than 6 points per game, the difference is substantial.

Conclusion

We reject the null hypothesis, the value of a dual-threat QB is both significant and substantial compared to a pure passer. In terms of fantasy football relevance, with all other statistics being equal, it is beneficial to roster a QB which has a higher expected rushing yard total.
